			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><div class="postbody">Law's vary from state to state, so I can only relay this as coming from Florida, where I work in a correctional facility.
<br />

<br />
This is at the county level. Both sentanced and unsentanced Inmates are treated the same in this setting.
<br />

<br />
Upon being booked into the county jail, you are chared $10.00 for that process. You stay for more than a day, and at the end of the week, you are chared somewhere in the neighborhood of $15.00 for partial pay of meals. This is pro-rated if your not there the entire week.
<br />

<br />
If you have no money, a lien is placed against your account. We will provide anything necessary (food, medication) but you will have that money owed to the county jail. Come back into jail at just about any time with money in your pocket, and you owe the county money, and it's gone. No questions asked.
<br />

<br />
There are other fee's associated with going to jail, but this has nothing to do really with the court system per se. It's all processed and recorded by the county. This is legal within florida state laws, and I think it's a great way to get at least some of the tax payers money back. 
<br />

<br />
You have to pay money to live on the street. Why shouldn't you have to pay money for breaking the law, or even just being in jail awaiting trial? It's all at a reduced cost anyway, and I see family members dropping off money and such for them all the time. They can pay at least a little bit imo.<span class="gensmall"></span>


				</div></td>
			</tr>
