			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><div class="postbody">Poppa,
<br />

<br />
While a lot of your viewpoints are refreshing, I think your not quite up to speed on this topic. As far as "condoning" and/or "justifying" anything my city/county does or dosen't do, I'm hardly in a position to make policy. Also, consider that my county is simply exercising the right's assigned to it by the the state supreme court of florida. So calling something legal and binding can hardly be called extorting. That's the law here. You don't like it, I guess you have 2 choices. Don't break the law, or break the law in another state. /shrug
<br />

<br />
As far as a community feeling what ever they feel, you again show your lack of knowledge in this case. The community has next to nothing to do with policy about who stays in jail, and who dosen't. That's judges, SA's, and sheriff's office/City PD's deal. Fed's have nothing to do with my county, we don't house any fed prisoners there (and I am unfamiliar with what their policy is, so I won't comment on it).
<br />

<br />
You said most people in jail don't do any harm? That's a laugh Poppa. Most drug offenders (barring marijuana in most cases) cause considerable harm. Going cocaine up, any of them are capable of  murder, robbery, rape, home invasion, and a host of other crimes. Sure, a lot of them don't get that far, but the possibility (and a large one at that), is there. You want 10,000 junkies roaming the streets at a time? I sure as hell don't, but if you'd like, maybe we could arrange to transport all of ours to your home town, and we'll drop all charges as long as they don't come back. You can even make it illegal to arrest them for drug charges if you'd like, I'm sure they'd love that.
<br />

<br />
Also consider your comments about people being "just drug offenders" simply isn't true. Quite a large amount are sellers, who pose as drug addicts so the courts will feel sorry for them, and give them less time, shove them in the general direction of a drug treatment center, and back out selling dope they go. 
<br />

<br />
In some ways I do agree with you about victimless crimes, but sadly, only with marijuana. It's harmless really (other than to the user). I'd rather have alcohol banned than pot. I worked intake bringing in new prisoners for 7 years. Never had to fight 1 that was high, but probably 1 in 4 that were drunk /shrug.
<br />

<br />
Also, consider that the majority of people in county jails ARE NOT innocent. Roughly 40% of what we get are repeat offenders in for violations of parole/probation. Another 25% are either already commited to DOC (department of corrections/prison) or waiting to go there as they have been convicted and sentanced (or have recieved county jail time and are working off their sentance with us).
<br />

<br />
Unconstitutional practices? I do believe it's been challenged Poppa, and the counties won. They don't charge near everything they spend, just a small %. As far as budgeting dependant on a cash supply from prisoners, do you think they're morons? We budget as though no one pays us. All that extra money goes into paying for medical care/food that we do get, but it's hardly a given we're getting xxx % per year. In the grand scheme, we don't get a lot back.
<br />

<br />
But, if you'd rather go on paying for people to live for free, that's purely your choice. Considering (where I live) that that SA has about a 99% conviction rate (if it goes to trial. Most don't because of several factors), I'm pretty confident that the large majority of people in jail that aren't convicted are in fact guilty.<span class="gensmall"></span>


				</div></td>
			</tr>
