				<td colspan="2"><div class="postbody">Chakan, 
<br />

<br />
I think your quite confused about what prison is supposed to be. Rehab was given up on in or around the 1970's. There is no such thing, short of court ordered drug rehab for those offenders. 
<br />

<br />
Prison is 1 thing and 1 thing only. Punishment for being convicted of a crime. You forfeit time off your personal life to live among your peers for a set amount of time. Sure, you might learn some basic tradeskill while incarcerated, but all in all, prison does in no way shape or form promote someone to being a better person than when they came to the institution.
<br />

<br />
In jail, you should not be able to get a degree. You should not be able to surf the net. You should not get to do nearly anything that people abide by the law get to do. You should have to start at zero, at work your way up in priviliges. If you screw up, you go back a step. This is positive reinforcement. As it is now, people go an hang out wit there homies and chill. 3 hots and a cot an all that.
<br />

<br />
No, prison or jail should not be fun. But, sadly, for a lot of people, it is a step up in life, so those types of people won't ever feel like something has been taken away in the first place. But I stand by the fact that prison is for punishment, for doing something wrong. It should be harder than it is now by a far stretch. Harder in the sense that Inmates want to rejoin society and stay out. But that dosen't happen. Most people that are in jail or prison have been there before. Character flaw? Hard childhood? I don't care. For too long people both in and out of the jail/prison system have been blaming everything but the person responsible for the reason they're incarcerated. It's a sham. It's bogus, and everyone should be well sick and tired of the excused these people blurt out at every stop in their lives. 
<br />

<br />
Since you like to look up stats and figures so much, why don't you find out how much taxpayers pay per year for the last ten years in your state for convicted felons. I assure you, the amounts are staggering. These types of people (not all in prison/jail, but the majority) are leeches on society. They are ticks that suck the life from people that do the "right" thing, that contribute to society in some positive form. 
<br />

<br />
Locking someone anywhere for any amount of time does next to nothing Chakan, your right. But that really dosen't happen as you put it. Prison has a lot more freedom overall that county jails. Only the worst of the worst, the true animals are confined to their cells most of the time they're in the system (and usually these types will never see a free ray of sunshine ever again). But, more to the point, what do you do with them? How do you show them there is a better life? You really can't. That has to come from them. There are rules in society. If you don't follow them, you go to jail. You keep doing the wrong thing, and eventually, you end up in prison (next to no one goes to prison the first time the commit a felony and are convicted, except for severe/violent crimes normally). That's the way it is. If they don't want to go back to prison/jail, perhaps they should stop being deviant, and take a stab at living free, instead of living to wait to go back.
<br />

<br />

<br />
As far as your "real time ticker" for 1/2 of all people being in jail for misd marijuana possession, I highly doubt it. But, you'd probably believe it (why else would you post it?). On the flip side, I fully believe marijuana should be decriminalized. It's a pointless law. We dump millions of dollars into enforcement for no good reason other than people think it's "bad". Alcohol is far far worse, at least in my opinion (but there is a good amount of evidence to back that up).<span class="gensmall"></span>


