				<td colspan="2"><div class="postbody">Bigjit,
<br />

<br />
I find myslef having to respond to 2 longish posts so I'm gonna try and condence it down a little into principals rather than direct reply to your statements.
<br />

<br />
"Rehabilitation" was a concept that was discarded in the 70s (after about 3 minutes of actually trying it.  It was in my view an evil thing to do.  You should not brainwash people into thinking the way you do.  Soviets and Chinese "rehabilitate" political dissedents by putting them in slave labor camps and working them litterally to death.
<br />

<br />
The arguement you make however if you extend the logic makes it sound like we should just sentence people for life for all crimes.  People mature with the passage of time.  Letting them have access to education, vocational training and constructive activities in prison is a way of priming the process with social mechanisms that DO cause people to rethink their philosophies and motivations.
<br />

<br />
The danger with the arguements that you make is that you are setting up systems by which government can subvert the basic liberties and constitutional rights our citizens have in the US.  Prisoners are being denied access to the courts.  Prisons are becoming the number one source for cheap labor.  If you book a flight now a days or call a customer service number you may very well be talking to a prisoner.  That office furnature you have?  Made in the US? May very well have been made by a prisoner.
<br />

<br />
If we continue on this path we will create an environment where the prison systems will become an integral part of our economy.  We will HAVE to continue to find more prisoners to keep the engine going and therefore find ourselves losing more rights as law abiding citzens as the "machine" seeks new way to keep itself alive.
<br />

<br />
In California, the jails and prisons as well as the businesses that serve them and utilize the under minimum wage labor are already the second largest industry after agriculture.  Let me say that again, with the wealth of technology and aerospace in California, prisons are a larger part of the economy than all the Sun microsystems and Ciscos put together.
<br />

<br />
We are at a critical juncture where if we are not careful, ALL of our poor will be shackeled and forced to labor for less than a free law abiding person would make.  Making prisoners "pay" for room and board is a key element in making that economic shift a reality as it creates a need for income to be generated.
<br />

<br />
Have you read Dickens?  This isnt exactly a new concept and the horrors and evils it visited on society at the begining of the industrial age will be nothing if we reinstitute it today with our techonology and information awareness.<span class="gensmall"></span>


