				<td colspan="2"><div class="postbody">Poppa,
<br />

<br />
While I understand completely where your coming from on some of your arguments, I am not sure exactly where we jump onto those tracks. It appears to me we were discussing 1 thing, and it totally got shifted into something completely different from 1 post to the next.
<br />

<br />
For the record, I don't agree with Inmate labor in that sense that you have just discribed unless certain criteria is met, and that some money the inmate has earned is set aside for their release (if they are ever to get out), or could be sent "home" to help out with bills etc. Almost like a work release, only your never released in that sense. 
<br />

<br />
I am some what confused in what your referring to as far as Inmate labor though. It dosen't happen in Florida to my knowledge, or that I've even ever heard. From what I know of corrections history, inmate labor was put down in the 70's by the supreme court. I don't know if anything's different about what your describing, or if some area has been allowed to forray into having inmates work for some small sum of money, so as to save someone money, but if that's what it is, it's definatly wrong. Having inmates work on a farm to provide food for the inmates? Fine. Having inmates work to improve the community they live in? Fine. But renting out groups of inmates to private industry must not and should not ever be allowed. Is this what your discribing? I'm not entirely sure.
<br />

<br />
Keep in mind Poppa, that I was talking about a county level facility with around a constant 1100 headcount. We have no machine shops, or any other kind of trade skill orientated learning evironment. Our class rooms are just that, class rooms, with computers for learning (not hooked up to the internet). We certainly encourage people not to come back as much as possible, but seriously, it's on those people to do so. Nothing I do is anyone's responsibility but my own. If I make a mistake, I must pay for it in some way (unless I don't get caught). Teaching career criminal's their abc's has done next to nothing but create smarter criminals. 1 our of 10 saved? I'd rather just keep the whole 10 down, and save the extra money for that gifted kid that can't afford a college education, but that's just me.
<br />

<br />
And no, I never said anything about sentancing people to life in prison for all crimes. Quote where you got that from, or where your extending what I've said, and I'll try to make it a little more clear on what I mean/where I'm going with it. I realize I may sound like a nazi sometimes, but I'm very passionate about debates involving things like this, because so very few american's actually have a clue as to what goes on in jail/prison. They watch american me or some HBO undercover america segment and think that's real. Well, it isn't. Not even a large % of it is.<span class="gensmall"></span>


